1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Okay.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Today is Friday, September 16, 2011.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:23,000
My name is Joe Maneye of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

5
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:31,000
I'm with videographer John Bishop and we are in Atlanta, Georgia to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

6
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:39,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Let me just make a quick note. We are not recording to XD cards. That's correct, John.

8
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Yeah, that's correct.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
We are delighted and it's a real privilege and honor to be with Ms. Kathleen Neal Cleaver today.

10
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:59,000
And let me note for the tape that we have two other persons who are sort of auditing our interview today,

11
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Ron Miss Rondy Gaines and Mr. Henry Gattes.

12
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Ms. Cleaver, what a privilege and pleasure to be with you.

13
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Well, thank you. Thank you for coming.

14
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Welcome. Let me start. We mentioned before we kicked off the recording that there's an awful lot of history that we could talk about here.

15
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:22,000
And why don't we pick up the story about 1954, obviously with Brown and Vietnam and move on from there?

16
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:30,000
I like that because 1954 is a turning point in Vietnam.

17
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:36,000
It's a turning point in the United States because of the Brown decision.

18
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
And it was also a turning point in my life. I was nine years old.

19
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Now why was Vietnam in 1954 a turning point? Because the world of imperialism came crashing down in 1954.

20
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:57,000
French imperialism was destroyed in Vietnam by the Vietnamese.

21
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:05,000
And that inspired African colonies to understand that it was possible to defeat the French army.

22
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:11,000
But set in motion a wave of anti-colonial liberation movements.

23
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:25,000
1954 in the United States was the profound transformation in the consciousness of black people when they saw the United States Supreme Court throw out the principle of separate but equal.

24
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:36,000
And even though the case said separate but equal separate but equal was valid in education, it said that it can't be.

25
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,000
It has to be thrown out. The decision was about education.

26
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:50,000
However, the way that decision was interpreted by the black community was that segregation was against the Constitution.

27
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:00,000
It unleashed all types of popular uprisings. You can't have segregated libraries, a protest, a protest at the swimming pool, a protest at the bus, a protest at this.

28
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:13,000
So that all around the country where black people were segregated, it inspired protest spontaneously and enthusiastic upheaval in our community.

29
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:24,000
But it also simultaneously inspired hatred and viciousness in the segregationist community, particularly when you look at a place like Mississippi.

30
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:35,000
And the murder of Emmett Till, who was one of those children, who would be affected by the end of segregation in education, which they had a horror.

31
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
This was like a horror to segregationists.

32
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:44,000
So being nine years old, I'm pretty forgiving, I have stuff people who are okay with that.

33
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:55,000
So being a child, being nine years old in 1954, of course I was impressionable and I was aware that my parents were involved in some civil rights activity.

34
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
I was aware of the excitement.

35
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:06,000
But we left Alabama, my father was on the faculty at Tuskegee Institute and my mother worked at the Institute.

36
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:24,000
And if it's a very cohesive, small community around the campus, I left all that with my parents because my father was hired to work in the foreign aid program in India.

37
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:33,000
And the reason he was selected in India had to do with his training in community development and his work with rural farmers in Alabama.

38
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:46,000
The United States .4 program that Truman implemented in after World War II had this position of, we will help resist communism.

39
00:04:46,000 --> 00:05:04,000
The notion that India may have a powerful communist movement was something the United States was anxious to prevent.

40
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:17,000
And they developed a community development program to be run in villages to help the villagers and my father was hired as a technical director in this kind of work.

41
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:25,000
So we moved from Tuskegee Institute, John Patterson I believe was a governor of Alabama.

42
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:30,000
It was a little bit before segregation today, segregation tomorrow, segregation forever, but it was still that mindset.

43
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Into a place where Nehru was the president, it's the land of Gandhi, it's the land of independence.

44
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:57,000
I came into a society that was moving from being dominated and directed by British imperial rulers to being ruled by representatives of the Indian people.

45
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:05,000
And so they were changing the names of the streets, they were moving into an Indian society away from a British colonial society.

46
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:13,000
So I saw all that and I saw a government that had lots of dark skinned people.

47
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:30,000
I saw all sorts of things and so I was so young I'm not . . . the upside is that it became very obvious to me that there's no coherent way that someone could say people can't vote or can't govern themselves because of their color, because of their dark.

48
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:40,000
So all the propaganda of white supremacy, which probably wasn't going to get to me anyway because of my parents, it was just blown out of the water.

49
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:51,000
So after two years living in India, my father was transferred to the Philippines, which was another society in Asia that had been colonized, but this one had been colonized by the United States.

50
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
But it was also independent.

51
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:05,000
As the Vietnam War is unfurling and colonial movements are developing in anti-colonial movements are developing in Africa and in Asia.

52
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:11,000
You know, I'm just growing up in this atmosphere and the work that my father's doing is highly political.

53
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:20,000
Even though I probably didn't even know the meaning of the word political, I was in a highly political environment and I was very influenced. These are my norms.

54
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:28,000
You know, eliminate segregation, eliminate colonialism from a child.

55
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:43,000
And so we would come back briefly to visit the United States back and forth up until I went to high school in 1961 at a Quaker boarding school.

56
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:56,000
My parents stayed in Africa. I mean, stayed living abroad, but I came to go to this high school. I just so happened I went to the same high school as Julian Bond, although he had already graduated.

57
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:57,000
And so my...

58
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,000
The George School in your cold outfit?

59
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Yes. So I have this, you know, I mean, it's a very unique understanding of the potential of people of color to rule themselves, to govern themselves.

60
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And then I come to a Quaker School which had been, and I was on the impression that they were advocates of nonviolent peaceful change.

61
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
So I enrolled in 61.

62
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:29,000
About the time I was about to graduate, May of 63. This is when Birmingham's blowing up.

63
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:38,000
And this is when the students in Birmingham are demonstrating in Bokiners bringing out the police dogs and Martin Luther King is in jail.

64
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:50,000
And the SNCC students are down in Albany on the barricades. They're going to jail demonstrating. It was a jail-no-bayow campaign in Albany.

65
00:08:50,000 --> 00:09:04,000
And they're all demonstrating. And I saw in the Philadelphia newspaper a photograph on the front page. It was a photograph of a paddy wagon from the back and there were these girls, high school girls in the back.

66
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:12,000
And they were all singing. And they were being carted off to jail. And I was just so intrigued. I said, these are girls. They're high school girls. I'm a high school girl.

67
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:20,000
These are people in Georgia challenging segregation and going to jail. And I was just extraordinarily impressed. I mean, it was more than impressed.

68
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:33,000
I wanted to be like them. And we had a program at my high school called Assembly. So I decided that I wanted to say something about what was going on.

69
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And I'll be. Now there's a trigger. It's a boarding school. So you have a dining hall. And there is a note put up at the dining hall outside that said, I suggest that we have a fast in the dining hall in support of the students in Albany who are praying and fasting in jail.

70
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:14,000
And so the next day there's another note outside the dining hall. And a boy in my class said that he thought that that was not a good idea. He said something more critical.

71
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:25,000
And that there should be a more co-operative solution than fasting and nonviolent protest.

72
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:34,000
So I looked at that note. I said, what is wrong with him? I was so impressed that these girls are going up against these vicious racists in Georgia.

73
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:46,000
So I just said, well, who in the world is he to know what somebody in Georgia should do? So I wanted to defend the students. But I didn't really know enough.

74
00:10:46,000 --> 00:11:03,000
So I went to Philadelphia. We had, so I had, quicker schools have something called work camp. You have to do work camp before you graduate. And our work camp was in Philadelphia. And they took us to different social activist centers.

75
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And one of them was called fellowship house. And when I had gone to fellowship house, I met a woman named, or I heard about a woman named Praithia Hall, who was an activist in SNCC.

76
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:21,000
And so I said, well, I'm going to go talk to Praithia. And she's going to explain to me what this nonviolent movement is so I can defend it.

77
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:34,000
So I got on the train and I went to fellowship house. And I said, I would like to see Praithia Hall. And I said, well, she's not here. She's left. She's gone to Georgia.

78
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:49,000
So whoever it was, it was a tall painter who lived there. And I said, well, you're here. I want you to explain nonviolence to me because it's very important for me to understand this.

79
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:03,000
And he said, well, I'll do the best I can, but Praithia should just say no, no, you have to do it. So he sat me down and gave me his interpretation. Bunch, bunky, bunchy, he was an artist. And we became friends for a long time.

80
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:24,000
And he articulated this central principle of transformation and how you engage in love and compassion and you are supposed to win over your enemies by loving them and not retaliate when they attack you.

81
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:41,000
And I think I was about 17 years old and this was a very appealing to me. I just very intrigued that this was their philosophy, that what they were doing had a meaning. And it made me see them as even braver than I understood from reading about the men in the newspaper.

82
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:53,000
So I was very impressed and I wrote out this little speech that I was going to make to get this guy who said it was, we should find a more collaborative way of doing things.

83
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:04,000
And I went to the painting teacher who I knew well because I had taken her classes and she was in charge of assembly on Thursday.

84
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:14,000
So I said, can I make a presentation on Thursday at assembly? She said, oh yes, Kathleen, but she didn't ask me what it was about. And I didn't tell her.

85
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:26,000
So we have our Thursday assembly and they say, well, she would like to make a presentation. So I get up and I have my speech and I read it and I tell them to protest against the students.

86
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:41,000
And I think that's wrong that they should be understood. This is their reasons for doing it. And those who don't agree with them should at least respect them because they are doing something about racial injustice and the very difficult circumstances.

87
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:52,000
So I thought that Quakers agreed with nonviolent protest, but they taught nonviolent protest. At least that's what I thought.

88
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:06,000
Now I have to tell you something about the racial dynamics of the school. It was about 400 students in grades 9 through 12 and of the 400 students, four of them were black.

89
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:16,000
And of the four black ones, me and another student were from Tuskegee. And one student was a day student and one student was an African foreign student.

90
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:30,000
So basically I'm talking to an entirely middle America, Quaker, white audience of students and teachers. They were not enthusiastic.

91
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:41,000
In fact, they were very upset. And they started calling me a radical and they said this and so I said, well, we have to have more discussion.

92
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:51,000
So I went back to French and I got the person and I said, you have to come to church school. They wanted to discuss this. I don't know anymore. So I brought him and we had discussions.

93
00:14:51,000 --> 00:15:04,000
So that's what happened at the end of high school for me while the protest was going on in Birmingham, my campus, the protest was around my attitude and my discussion of Albany.

94
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:16,000
So I would say from then that was the summer of 63. I was very focused on civil rights activism. I wanted to do that. I wanted to be like those students.

95
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:26,000
I wanted to go on those protests that they were on. But I had to go where my parents took me. That summer was the March on Washington.

96
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:37,000
My parents came back. We had family in Baltimore and we were visiting our family in Baltimore in August of 1963.

97
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:48,000
So I wanted my parents to take me to the March on Washington. Well, oh no. They say you cannot go to that. There will be violence. It's going to be violent.

98
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Which is what was the word in Washington. This was to prevent people from coming. So I was just very upset that I could be so close, but I couldn't go.

99
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:16,000
And so in the fall I went to over my no, I didn't have the capacity at the 17 18 to be able to do things that my parents wouldn't allow.

100
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:22,000
So this all looks in change.

101
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:35,000
I didn't understand their opposition. I really didn't. And it wasn't violent. But the propaganda that had gone out in Washington and my father was working in Washington. He was a foreign service officer.

102
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:43,000
So part of that was his caution. But the other part was I think they did believe. I mean, my mother and father both had been active.

103
00:16:43,000 --> 00:17:00,000
So my father had been involved in the effort to desegregate the quite primary in Texas back in the 30s. And my mother had been involved in the Southern Negro Youth Congress, which protested education segregation.

104
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:11,000
And she used a beneficiary of consent decree between NAACP and the state of Virginia to be able to go to school in graduate school in Michigan.

105
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:28,000
Because you could have segregated elementary, high school, and college. But there was no graduate school for black. So for her to go to graduate school, she benefited from the agreement that the state of Virginia would pay tuition for anyone who was accepted. And so she went to Michigan.

106
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:50,000
And so it wasn't that they weren't for civil rights. That that was the attitude of 1963. And so I went away to college to Oberlin. My parents had picked out Oberlin. I thought this was a fine college that I should go. Oberlin happened to be a hotbed of civil rights, which I didn't really know.

107
00:17:50,000 --> 00:18:05,000
But also I didn't really know much about colleges because from the time I was nine, I was living away from the United States. We had come back in the late 50s. I'd gone to high school in Baltimore for a year.

108
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:22,000
My brother died in 58. And 59, I went to Baltimore public school. And then we went back and lived in Africa. And so then I came back and went to boarding school and finished.

109
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:31,000
So I didn't really have a lot of exposure. I didn't really know a lot about colleges. And I had been geared to go to Oberlin. I applied and got in. And I went there.

110
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:40,000
And there were some friends from Tuskegee, there. And there was an active civil rights group who were both black and white. And there weren't enough.

111
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:47,000
I mean black students there for probably more than some of the other schools. And so I was I was influenced.

112
00:18:48,000 --> 00:19:06,000
I shouldn't say influenced. I was in an atmosphere that was very conducive. Carrie McWilliams was one of the faculty there. There was a Japanese professor named, I'm not remembering his name right now, who was quite radical.

113
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:22,000
And there was this. There were a lot of speakers who were coming to Oberlin and talking about different protests. The one I remember in particular was about Danville.

114
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:37,000
There was a huge protest against segregation in Danville, Virginia. And there were lots and lots of I guess you'd say marches and police brutality. And there was a documentary about it.

115
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:50,000
So that was like very eye opening. All these are the things that are happening. And the Mississippi summer project was being planned for the summer of 64 when I would be.

116
00:19:50,000 --> 00:20:12,000
The end of my freshman year. But the beginning of the freshman year was when the children were killed in the 16th Street Baptist Church. That was in September. And then in a few months, the president in the United States was killed in Texas.

117
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:31,000
So I remember that the group that I, my friends, we were all quite upset and didn't know what the civil rights struggle was going to be like because we thought then that president Kennedy was supportive.

118
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:57,000
When he was killed and Lyndon Johnson with his southern draw became the president, it didn't look. It didn't sound right. No one in 1963 ever, ever expected none of the young people ever expected president Johnson to be an advocate of civil rights because he'd voted against everything.

119
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:15,000
He was a representative of Texas. So he represented Texas views. So I wanted to go to Mississippi, but, but I actually couldn't quite manage to do it.

120
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I didn't, I didn't think I was sturdy enough or smart enough or, you know, college freshman, it takes a while to get a sense of who you are. So, so I didn't go to the Mississippi summer project.

121
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:54,000
I didn't sign up for it. I actually quit college and went to stay in Washington and had a few jobs. I didn't really didn't actually like college. I was so disappointed. I thought it was going to be exciting and stimulating and dramatic.

122
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:07,000
I had this very exaggerated view of what college was going to be and it wasn't all that. So I just went and got a job working in the various agency, government agencies.

123
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:13,000
One of the jobs I think I just want to ask is I wonder how you think about it. In retrospect, was I think the area of relation service?

124
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:19,000
One of your chores, as I understand, was to type up certain reports.

125
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:32,000
When I got the job at the Peace Corps, my job was to, there's something very low, like a GS7. And I think I had to put little flyers in racks and sign out the Peace Corps film.

126
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:46,000
And a man who worked there, Richard Thornell, said he was going to go work over at the Human at the CRS Community Relations Service, which is a brand new agency set up under the 64 Civil Rights Act.

127
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:56,000
And he wanted me to come and work as a secretary. He said you could do more than this. So I agreed and I got a raise and I got to be a secretary.

128
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:08,000
And my job was to type reports in triplicate, working for the government. And so he would go like the one I remember most vividly was Cleveland.

129
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:20,000
He went to Cleveland after riots because the Community Relations Service sent teams into or teams would be one or two people in a secretary maybe.

130
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:29,000
Teams into areas of conflict and then they would make a report to the Community Relations Service about the conflict.

131
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:44,000
And so I would type up all the things he said about the Huff area and Cleveland and economics. I mean, it's almost when you read the reports that something is going to blow up.

132
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:57,000
I mean, it's not a unpredictable situation in the ghetto environment that they described that this, you know, conflagrations, riots, rebellions, what happened.

133
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:12,000
So I did that over and over and over and I believe in February Malcolm X was murdered.

134
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:27,000
Now, I hadn't actually gotten to hear him in person but I was aware of him. I would have liked to have gone to hear him in person.

135
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:35,000
I'm sorry for laughing. When I said I'd like him, I'd like to have heard Malcolm X a person.

136
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:48,000
When I was in, let's go see the Baltimore Washington, one of the, there was a flyer out and it said come here Malcolm X debate James Baldwin.

137
00:24:48,000 --> 00:25:00,000
I don't know where it was. Well, this was not the one that I, the one that I tried to go to was at a mosque, one of these Muslim mosques.

138
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:13,000
And I did get my father to take me. I'm not sure if my mother came. Anyway, we went to this, I think it was in Baltimore.

139
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:26,000
We went to this address and my father's fairly light skin and I think my hair was straightened at the time.

140
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:36,000
Let me get there. Muslims at the door look at this very, very, actually my mother did come. My mother and father and me, they all went.

141
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:42,000
They look at this very, very carefully and they finally decided it was okay for my mother to come. It was probably okay.

142
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:47,000
But I could not come in. They would not let me come in because they thought I was white.

143
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:55,000
So I said, well, my father's, this is my father, this is my mother. How could they come in and I can't come in.

144
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:01,000
And they just finally, I guess we just wouldn't leave and they let us in.

145
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:14,000
But it wasn't any Malcolm X and James Baldwin. It was a movie. I mean, it was like a TV tape of a debate between Malcolm X and James Baldwin.

146
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:32,000
And then, you know, so to be my age and aware of the things I was aware of and to see, you know, President Kennedy is assassinated and Martin Luther King is sent to jail and Malcolm X is being killed.

147
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:37,000
This is not, this country is not going in the right direction.

148
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:50,000
So, I think we're back. We're going to pick up the story in 1965 and let me just make a note. We're going to take out the prior little clip.

149
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:55,000
Okay. We think it's a travel in the 60s.

150
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:02,000
Well, you can imagine my parents were quite distressed when I told them I wasn't going to go back to college.

151
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:23,000
And so I spent that year working in DC. I was working with the CRS. I had a really good experience because the director, not the director, the deputy director was Roger Wilkins, who was, say, an attorney and a civil rights attorney.

152
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:34,000
And a very good, good person. I think the director was some, it was in the department of commerce. It was someone else.

153
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:51,000
But to be with Richard Thornell and Roger Wilkins and to have that as a job and to be in this to hear the kinds of things they said and Roger Wilkins actually knew my father.

154
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:13,000
And I meet this person. Yes, my father had a position in Sierra Leone. He was the representative of the, he was the representative of the United States in Sierra Leone when he was first sent there because it was a British colony.

155
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:38,000
So the United States couldn't actually have an ambassador. So we lived in free town for a while in 61 and I met one of the Crossroads Africa students who came there also with P-score that my father, because he was the American representative, he had a party to bring these people who had come to Africa.

156
00:28:38,000 --> 00:29:00,000
And I, one of them, I met, who ended up, his name was James Thomas. He ended up being a law student who was working for CRS. So here I'm meeting people who are interested in law and civil rights and justice in ways that I wasn't particularly exposed to.

157
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:25,000
But I'm meeting them in ways in which I actually get to know them and hear what they are about. In fact, James Thomas, who was a law student, I had been invited, I think when I was in high school to come up to Yale Law School by him. I was in high school, he was in law school, but he invited me to come to his court.

158
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:40,000
I met all of your first trial and I met of all people because it was Yale Law School because it was 1962 or whatever year it was, 62 or 63. I met Marion Wright, who was a law student in his class, who later became Marion Wright Edelman.

159
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:50,000
I also met Blanke on her name.

160
00:29:50,000 --> 00:30:03,000
Who was the DC representative? Ellen their homes. She wasn't North. Marion Wright and Ellen their homes, who were in his class at law school. Or they may have been a bit ahead of him.

161
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:20,000
So this is the atmosphere of inspiration and education that was, I don't think I encountered any types of people close to me that were against civil rights or against the movement.

162
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:33,000
So everything was encouraging. It was all things going in the same direction except my parents were quite unhappy that I wasn't in college and they wanted me to go back.

163
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:38,000
I really was having a great time and didn't want to go back, but I did want to go to New York.

164
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:52,000
So I applied to a college in New York called Barnard and was accepted and they advertised the fact that Barnard is in New York. This is where you learn by being in New York.

165
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:03,000
So I liked that idea. I wanted to go to New York. So they were happy. I was happy. I went to New York after about, let's say, three weeks of Barnard.

166
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:15,000
I said, this is dumb. I was at Oberlin and actually worked and studied and went to class and got okay grades.

167
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:21,000
But when I got to Barnard, the classes weren't that interesting and after a while I just started going.

168
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And I had met that summer, a man named George Ware, who was in SNCC. He had been in SNCC in Atlanta and he had actually, I'm sorry, he had been affiliated with SNCC from the Tuskegee Student Movement.

169
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:46,000
He was a director of something called, or he was a leader, I don't know if he was a director, of something called Tile, Tuskegee Institute Advancement League.

170
00:31:46,000 --> 00:32:00,000
And they were engaged in the big, huge protest in Selma.

171
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:09,000
But the Selma to Montgomery March was one aspect and the Tuskegee to Montgomery March was another aspect.

172
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:17,000
So I was meeting someone who was like one of the actual SNCC leaders. I was very excited.

173
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:28,000
And the important thing about meeting George, there was a graduate student who lived in Washington, whose mother had been a teacher in Tuskegee and knew my mother.

174
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:37,000
And he found out I was there that summer and came to visit and we ended up dating. And George Ware was his best friend.

175
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:47,000
So that's how I met George and long story short, George ultimately hired me as his assistant in the campus program in SNCC.

176
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:57,000
But before he did that, I had this very transformative conversation, not a conversation.

177
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:16,000
Because I'd never met him before, when we first met, he started recounting what had happened in Tuskegee and the demonstrations and how they built up the student energy and how they had decided they were going to challenge the...

178
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:32,000
It wasn't just racism, they were challenging. What they wanted to challenge was the manner in which the civil rights protest in Alabama in general in Tuskegee in particular was being geared to a...

179
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:37,000
He thought it was too collaborative. He said these people think they can work together.

180
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:49,000
You know, that there's a city council they want to get people to register, to vote, and to hold office. Let's say they were...

181
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:53,000
Let's say they were nine seats.

182
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:05,000
Making County was 88% black. Tuskegee is the county seat.

183
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:20,000
So if the representation in voting even mildly reflected the demographics of the county, they could have an entirely black council.

184
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:30,000
But the TCA, Tuskegee Civic Association, wanted to not be assertive, but they wanted to participate. So they only ran two candidates.

185
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:36,000
And George thought that was horrible. And George said, look, we got to break this up. These people, they just...

186
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:44,000
They essentially want to get along, want this, and he said, I know what we can do. We'll have a...

187
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:52,000
Not exactly a demonstration, but they said we will go integrate their church in the white side of town. And he said, and then you'll see the parents come out.

188
00:34:52,000 --> 00:35:05,000
Because the citizens that come out with guns and detected children. So they consciously had demonstrations at the white churches and they got very, very upset. Everyone got very upset.

189
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:17,000
Then, Snick was also a very engaged voter registration. And he was telling me all about the Snick activities in Tuskegee.

190
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:24,000
But it was... I was in Tuskegee when I was a little child. It was very stable. And nobody was challenging...

191
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:33,000
They were challenging... Like... The segregation. They were challenging the Nile of the right to vote. But they weren't challenging themselves. Or their methods.

192
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:45,000
But that's what Tile was doing. And what actually ended up happening in Tuskegee was that Dr. Camille in a TCA backed down. They said, all right, you want to do things differently? Go ahead.

193
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:58,000
Which is very interesting. It's a very interesting transition. So George was telling me all this. And I'm not giving you the best description.

194
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:10,000
So, listening that evening to George Ware talk about Tuskegee and talk about Tile. It was just transformative. I saw Tuskegee in a light that I'd never seen it before.

195
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:25,000
But I also saw the power of black political action that I'd never seen before. And George became a mentor to me in terms of politics and understanding.

196
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:39,000
He was a chemist. So he's very analytical. But he never talked about chemistry. He talked about the activism. And he was from Alabama.

197
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:51,000
I mean, from rural Alabama. And he had gone to the graduate school at Tuskegee. He was brilliant. And his friend, who I was dating, was a student at the vet school. And he was an activist.

198
00:36:51,000 --> 00:37:05,000
He got kicked out. We're starting a black newspaper. So I went on that summer. I went on to Barnard, enrolled at Columbia. And George had a job in New York.

199
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:20,000
No, he had a job in New Jersey with a chemist, chemistry company, Hoffman LaRose. And Ernest had a fellowship with a, he was a veterinary student.

200
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:31,000
So he worked in some lab downtown in NYU. Just so happened that they went into an apartment on the Columbia campus. There was across the street from Barnard.

201
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:43,000
So we were very close. And I spent a lot of my time after the first three weeks of realizing these classes are going to be really dull. And the teachers weren't that smart. And the material isn't that interesting.

202
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:57,000
And I had a comparison. You said, I already been a freshman. So I had, I knew, you know, I'm a sophomore now. I had a comparison. This is not a good school. This is a waste of time. And I'm learning more hanging out with George and Ernest, which is true.

203
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:09,000
I met Stokeley Carmichael at their apartment. I met Ivan Holt Donaldson at a party at their house. And at summer I met Ivan Holt Donaldson. He had come from, he was a project director in Mississippi during the 64 summer project.

204
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:26,000
And he met me. He had gone to Michigan State and Ernest had gone to Michigan State. They kind of knew each other. So I felt in a very friendly environment. And Ivan Holt asked me, well, what are you doing? I said, well, I'm out of school for the summer. I'm looking for a job. And he said, well, I'm looking for a secretary.

205
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:29,000
How'd you like to work at Stoke?

206
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:42,000
Oh, my God. I've been wanting to work for Stoke ever since I heard about this demonstrations in Albany. You know, what time do I need to come? And he said, well, you know, he gave wrote in a little note told me to come such and such a time.

207
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:54,000
So I ran down 100th Avenue. I think it's just wrecking stairs. I ran down there. I was, it was like I'd gone to heaven. I'm working in Stoke. Oh, I had a job at Stoke. So I was so excited.

208
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:16,000
And what that job, that summer job was, I think I sat in the front of the building, front of his office at a desk. So I saw everyone who would come in and they'd have to stop and ask me what they wanted or whatever. So I got to see.

209
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:30,000
New York was the place that activists from the South would come for R&R. So if you needed to go to the dentist, it'd come out and Mississippi and go to tennis in New York. Or you just needed a break.

210
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:37,000
Or some people would just so burn out. They were through. They were through a snake. They come and they're going to go back to school.

211
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:47,000
Or they were doing whatever, but they'd all come through the New York Snick Office. And this New York office was a fundraising office. So they had the benefits. They had money.

212
00:39:47,000 --> 00:40:04,000
And this was 1966. This is the summer of 1966. And the day, the month that I get the job to work in the Snick Office in New York,

213
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:25,000
I think it's probably about two weeks after the call for black power in Greenville, Mississippi. And so Snick has already asked the executives, any people in a leadership position that are white, have been asked to leave.

214
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:38,000
And they're no longer any white leaders, but there's people who are in the organization who work like there's a bookkeeper in New York. But there's very, the numbers of people who are quite are diminishing.

215
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:54,000
The director of the New York office was a Chicano. Actually, her name was Elizabeth Sutherland. And at the time, people didn't identify as Mexican. So we didn't, I never thought what she was. She was a dark, dark haired woman.

216
00:40:55,000 --> 00:41:10,000
I guess we knew she wasn't black, but she was something to a brown skin. But she was being replaced by Ivanhoe. So there was a woman who was not a black person being replaced by a black activist out of Mississippi.

217
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:34,000
So I come into the mix and it's tremendous turmoil because black power has been articulated. Black power is the ideological or activist call that's replaced freedom now in the wake of the Voting Rights Act and the 1964 Civil Rights Act.

218
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:53,000
And it's also changed the dynamic of the leadership in SNCC because the executive committee and the program committee and chairman are now all part of the, I used to call them the black power faction. Everybody in SNCC is not on board for black power.

219
00:41:53,000 --> 00:42:02,000
Can I start this? Of course. In March, March, the 1966 that Stopy Carmichael asked John Lewis.

220
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:16,000
That would have been at a staff meeting at midnight. Yes, but he didn't oust him just oust him. There was an election that you have to understand that in SNCC, the role of chairman didn't really mean much. It meant the person who talked to the press.

221
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:27,000
Or if you could send somebody to answer a question. So nobody really mind whether John Lewis was a chairman. That was just his job. He would answer the question to ask John.

222
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:38,000
However, Stopy and his crew thought the chairman should be more active and they weren't pleased with his reelection and they had another vote.

223
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:45,000
John Lewis went to sleep thinking he was the chairman and he woke up and found out he was not the chairman. That Stopy was the chairman.

224
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:51,000
Were those stories that you heard through George and Ernest and you were across that spring? I don't know if it matters.

225
00:42:51,000 --> 00:43:01,000
I've really heard of after I got into SNCC because when I was in New York, but George and Stopy were good friends. So I'm sure everything I heard, I probably heard it from George.

226
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:08,000
Everything I heard about Stokley was in Stokley's favor. I never heard it from the perspective of John.

227
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:17,000
Let me ask one other thing too. For sure. Because you were now in the summer of 1966, but in January of 1966, someone you knew as a child is murdered and a skiebie and I just...

228
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:29,000
I think, yeah, let's let me get back to that because this goes this... Okay. While I was in New York, hold on, let me stop. I want to get...

229
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:37,000
And he didn't go to the same school I went to, but everyone in the same group, we all knew each other.

230
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:48,000
And he got involved in SNCC, in Tuskegee, after coming back from the Navy.

231
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:57,000
It was sort of unusual. I don't think any of my classmates signed up for the military that early.

232
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:04,000
But Samy joined the Navy, he got out, came back to Tuskegee and enrolled to college.

233
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:13,000
And he was extraordinarily active and George was one of the people who told me all about what Samy was doing because he was very...

234
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:24,000
Sort of like with me, he was very nurturing and... He was developing these activists. And Samy was one.

235
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:42,000
And Samy was active, very important because he was going back and forth between Alabama and Mississippi and looking at the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party operation and how that was problematic and then helping figure out how in Alabama they can have a black political party.

236
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:50,000
Not a party that's going to try and unseat Democrats, but an independent black political party that was started in Lounge County.

237
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:58,000
So, Stokely, Carmichael, Rap Brown and Samy Young and George, we're all working together in Lounge County.

238
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:11,000
So George plugged me into this. And midway through the school year, I think is in January, we heard on the radio, this Samy Young was murdered.

239
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:23,000
He was shot in the back at a gas station by this gas station attendant whose name was Marvin Seagrist.

240
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:32,000
And it was devastating. It was devastating to sneak. James Farman talked about how he'd gone to too many funnels.

241
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:41,000
And it was Samy's murder in Tuskegee. And when I say he was murdered, what he was doing was registering blacks to vote, going out in the county.

242
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:50,000
When I talked about 88% and the demographics, if Samy Young had had his wishes, he would have registered every black person then making counting.

243
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:57,000
And the clan could see what he was doing and there were death threats all the time. He had deacon for defense protecting his house.

244
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:13,000
So when Samy was murdered, the students kind of blew up, there was protests, there was demonstrations. George Ware felt guilty.

245
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:23,000
He felt that he was the one who had inspired and led and encouraged Samy to take all these risks to do what he was doing.

246
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:34,000
And when Samy was killed, he was in New York. So George made the decision to quit Hoffman the Rose and go back into the movement.

247
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:43,000
And he left New York and went, moved to Atlanta and took over the campus program in Atlanta.

248
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:55,000
I think in very shortly after, which is a big decision for someone who had a master's degree in chemistry, he rededicated himself to the movement.

249
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:16,000
And it was, because Samy was a veteran, Samy had been in Navy, because he was a veteran when Samy was killed, Samy took a position against the Vietnam War.

250
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:30,000
How can we actually support this war and ask men to register to fight when we have a veteran here who just murdered in cold blood and unarmed?

251
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:41,000
And that led Samy's death led to Julian Bond being asked. And he had just won an election for the state legislature here in Atlanta.

252
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:52,000
He was asked that he supports Nick's position against the Vietnam War. He had to actually read it, the actual statement. But he knew about it. And he said, yes, he did support it.

253
00:47:52,000 --> 00:48:03,000
If Nick took this position against the war, he would support it. Even though he was actually no longer in SNCC and had just one office in the state legislature, and so the news media in Georgia went berserk.

254
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:12,000
And he was denied his ability to take his seat in the Georgia legislature because he didn't support the Vietnam War.

255
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:20,000
And this went on and then went up to the Supreme Court before he won another election. He won again before he could even take his seat.

256
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:31,000
So it was a big, big deal in the movement that the transformations that happened in response to Samy's death and the transformation in George.

257
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:40,000
And I had joined the New York office a few weeks after Black Power and was in those changes.

258
00:48:40,000 --> 00:49:02,000
And when George got to Atlanta, he said he actually wanted me to come down and work for him. So at the end of, I think at the end of January of 67, I left New York and went to Atlanta.

259
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:13,000
And I was working constantly. I had never, ever in my life before or since spent so much time in meeting at a meeting and taking notes.

260
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:24,000
I think the first meeting I went to is Jim Foreman and a few other people because SNCC was in bad shape. It was financially in trouble.

261
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:44,000
So many people had burned out. Projects were being eliminated. Direct action wasn't the policy any longer. It was Black Power. And Stokeley was disturbing some of the fundraisers. I shouldn't say some of the people who were giving money to SNCC.

262
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:49,000
And at the Palestine statement, yet the native of the time you arrived in Atlanta?

263
00:49:49,000 --> 00:50:13,000
All those things were in play. The research, the research for the newsletter that was published by SNCC that criticized the Stern Gang and Morshidayan and the Israeli techniques of warfare that were very injurious to children.

264
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:29,000
They were something that I remember about a little cluster bombs that looked like toys. And all this research had been done by Manning Jack Minnes. And it was written up in a newsletter by a woman named Ethel Minor. And it was published.

265
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:50,000
And Stokeley was an advocate in the 67 war of the support of Egypt and not supporting Israel. And so he's very public about this. And many of the financial donors and supporters of SNCC were Jewish.

266
00:50:50,000 --> 00:51:13,000
And some of the whites that had worked in SNCC were Jewish. And they were horrified at this development. And I was told, I don't know if it's accurate, that Herbal Aphonti said he can smash the organization because that was not permissible in his mind to take that position.

267
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:36,000
And we went on our merry way. So by the time I got to SNCC, it was in a sort of a crisis. I didn't understand that this was the crisis of the crisis. But all the elements of crisis, people leaving drama, long meetings. I think the report that came out of this two or three day meeting was called Rock Bottom.

268
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:58,000
And we said, I was just taking notes. I was in my job to take notes. Taking notes. The meeting went on for about 14 hours. And they sort of, I was exhausted. But I couldn't stop. It was amazing to hear. To be in the James Foreman was my most, how would I put it?

269
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:17,000
The person I had admired the most of the civil rights leaders that I had seen at a distance. When I was in high school, there was a photograph of James Foreman in Jet Magazine. And it was taken in Mississippi. And it was riveting and unforgettable.

270
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:39,000
It was a picture taken in Mississippi. And on one side was this share, Mississippi Sheriff, your typical Southern Sheriff. And then on the other side facing toe to toe was Jim Foreman and his overalls and his bushy hair. And they were looking at each other. And he had an expression in his eyes.

271
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:51,000
That was so intense. It was like all the passion and anger and intelligence that he could muster to stop this man from doing what he was going to do.

272
00:52:51,000 --> 00:53:06,000
And I was just amazed. This is extraordinary. It's an extraordinary man. It's an extraordinary time. And he inspired this kind of devotion and attraction. People wanted to give their life for Jim Foreman. They do anything for Jim Foreman.

273
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:29,000
So yes, and I stay up for three days and take notes for Jim Foreman. And it was, I felt and I had asked my father to help me when he, when school was over, I went to work at SNCC for the summer. And then he said to me, I said, I wrote to him and I said,

274
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:45,000
this is so much more educational. I can't, I put it. I think I said, you're wasting your money paying tuition at Barnard. What I want you to do is give me the money that you would give to Barnard.

275
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:56,000
And I will get a much better education in SNCC than in Barnard. And he agreed. He said he'd do it for a year.

276
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:13,000
So, US doesn't understand tuition back then was about, about $800 a semester. So he would send me, I think he would send me checks every month. I don't remember getting a lump sum.

277
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:37,000
I can't imagine my father even giving me a lump sum. But so I went to SNCC in Atlanta, in Atlanta. After starting in the summer, I stayed through, through January. And came down to Atlanta.

278
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:49,000
And it really did feel like I was in the midst of a revolution because SNCC was in chaos. Although I wasn't sure it was chaos. I was just learning so much. But you know, the phone for getting cut off.

279
00:54:49,000 --> 00:55:05,000
And then we didn't have any more money to buy gas. And then the cars couldn't get repaired. So to get to work we had to hitchhike. And all this, I think I cut my hair and an Afro in New York. I got someone to cut it.

280
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:22,000
And when we got down to Atlanta, it didn't work that popular here in 67. And they called them Baby Haircut. So we would hitchhike. We would hitchhike to work because there were more cars, there were no money.

281
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:42,000
George Ware had an apartment that was actually belonged to Stokeley. And he lived there, Ernest Stevens lived there, Simuille Schutz lived there. And I moved in there. So we had our whole little campus program lived in one apartment. And the money my father sent me paid our rent because SNCC didn't have any money for salary.

282
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:56,000
So we were a cadre. And the project that George was working on when I came after the Rock Bottom report was a conference called Liberation will come from a black thing.

283
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:16,000
We were going to invite the student groups that had supported SNCC to a conference. This was very early in this issue, this notion of black students. So we're Negro student organizations, Negro student associations in various colleges.

284
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:35,000
But what the black power movement had stimulated was a change in consciousness. And there was a beginning, like out in California, the San Francisco State Negro student association became the black student union, one of the earliest. And so this idea of black students was fairly radical at this time.

285
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:58,000
So we were having planned this conference for a FISC because there was a SNCC support group at Tennessee State and there was a group at FISC that were very strong. And they had good programs, they had good leaders, they raised money, they were closely with the people in SNCC. So they were good home for the conference.

286
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:24,000
They got the buildings, we sent out the notices, we sent out the letters, we invited the students and we invited our speakers. Now we invited lots of speakers, Amiri Baraka, I think he was Lee Roy Jones at the time. We invited writer from Mississippi, she was a famous writer at the time, Margaret Walker, is that her name?

287
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:47,000
I have to look it up for you. It should have written a novel about the South, we invited people from, we invited Eldridge Cleaver who had published in ramparts and other activist scholars, Charles Hamilton from Columbia political scientists. These are the names I remember. I was the one that was sending out the invitations.

288
00:57:47,000 --> 00:58:08,000
So there was a program that was going to take place two weeks after our SNCC conference at Vanderbilt, which is the same city, but it's a white school. Vanderbilt had a program called Impact that the students controlled.

289
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:34,000
For their impact symposium, they had four people, they invited, Strom Thurman, Alan Ginsburg, Martin Luther King, and Stokeley Carmichael, and they were going to come at separate times. So Stokeley was the chairman of SNCC, but our conference was two weeks earlier.

290
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:59,000
Stokeley wasn't actually coming to the SNCC, it was called Liberation is Coming from Black Thing, but the newspapers in Nashville went stark, raving mad. This was a time when Stokeley Carmichael had been attacked as, he needed to be retroactively, his mother should take retroactive birth control, or he should be this, or can we deport him because he was a native of Trinidad.

291
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:15,000
So all this hostility about the impact symposium that he generated, the state legislature wanted the students not to invite him, and they refused.

292
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:29,000
But it's Fisk, a black school, decided that they would kick us out, that we couldn't have any rooms on their campus because our organization was organization, the Stokeley Carmichael was the chairman of.

293
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:39,000
So I was at Nashville with George Ware and Ernest and other students who were preparing the conference when they decided we couldn't have the rooms.

294
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:52,000
So here we are, we have all people coming and no place, and the other problem was that it was a blizzard. It was the Easter weekend of 67, there was a blizzard that shut down all the airports in the East Coast.

295
00:59:53,000 --> 01:00:05,000
Can I ask something? Right at the, oh, you're about to get to that, those days in Nashville, and I want to ask this, as best you can recall, if you can conjure this from the system.

296
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:21,000
It would have been, say, these months in early 67, it would have been your broadly speaking kind of where your mind was, your frame of mind about the struggle, about the nature of American society as you were continuing to examine and think about it.

297
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:33,000
I'm sorry, I'm sorry. No, what I'm saying, I'll give you this narrative and then I can do that very easily because it was all in flux, but, okay, so let's start back.

298
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:51,000
So here we are with all the students on their way and our conference is collapsing because now our speakers aren't kind of calm because they can't.

299
01:00:52,000 --> 01:01:09,000
They're going to not fly in and we have one speaker, Elder Scler, who can come because he arrives from California and the students there were well organized and they were able to get

300
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:24,000
father Woodruff, who was the pastor of a piscopal church. It was right on the edge of the campus. It wasn't controlled by the campus. He said we could have our conference at his church.

301
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:37,000
So we had a site. Elder Scler was coming. We had a speaker. And so we were okay. I was sitting there retiping the agenda, changing all the rooms, changing the speakers.

302
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:54,000
Then Elder Scler was brought into the room where I was typing and he was our savior. He was wonderful. We had a speaker. We were having a conference. And from what he said, he took one look at me and it was love at first sight.

303
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:12,000
But I wasn't love at first sight for me. I saw this giant standing in a doorway all the way to the top and he had been out of prison about three months. He had this very sort of mask like expression, no expression. He was just so standing there.

304
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:30,000
And I would say look pretty well. I don't want to say intimidating, but he could have been intimidating. So he kept asking me things about could I get him a room, could I get him a typewriter, could I do this, could I do that.

305
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:42,000
He had like trying to engage me and I didn't know that he was trying to get my attention. It never occurred to me that he was trying to help his crew.

306
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:55,000
Anyway, eventually it became clear that's what he was trying to do after the conference was all over. And he didn't leave because he said he was doing the story about Stokeley Carmichael.

307
01:02:55,000 --> 01:03:13,000
He was going to stay and write about impact. And I was going to stay and organized a fundraiser when Stokeley came. And so he helped me because I didn't know how to drive and have a car. He helped me pull together all these details.

308
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:20,000
By then I figured out he was trying to get my attention. He said to him, him longer to get my attention than any woman in his life.

309
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:38,000
So then we, I noticed he was very attracted to me and I was very impressed. And we went to, came back to Atlanta and we sat down and played a game of chess. And I beat him.

310
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:50,000
I don't know whether he let me beat him or he just thought I didn't know how to play. But George had taught me how to play chess. So I thought I was good. Anyway. And then we fell in love and the rest is history.

311
01:03:51,000 --> 01:04:18,000
In terms of how I was thinking, Eldridge had had the distinction of being a what we call it at that time black nationalist. I think that's probably somewhat misleading. But we use that term in a specific way, which meant an advocate of empowering the black community, repudiating racism, challenging all forms of injustice,

312
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:41,000
and analogizing ourselves, this came a little later, but analogizing ourselves to colonize people. I'm on that path. But in Nashville, in Nashville, a huge riot erupted after I left to go to be in a wedding on April 6, I believe, with the wedding.

313
01:04:41,000 --> 01:05:10,000
And the conference had been like March 27, 28, 29, something like that. So within a week of the conference, there was this huge uprising. And because the Tennessee legislature had been predicting violence, if Stokeley, Carmichael came, there's going to be violence. They got Michigan State helmets and training in riot control for their Nashville community.

314
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:30,000
They were police and they were so ready for this violence that they started to riot before Stokeley, Carmichael got there. I think it's like a little fight or conflict at a bar, sparked it. And they went on for days.

315
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:47,000
But the sense that we would fight, we would have to fight, we'd have to defend ourselves, we'd have to be armed, we'd have to learn about guerrilla tactics. All that was coming into play, but it wasn't.

316
01:05:47,000 --> 01:06:04,000
It hadn't crystallized because this was 67. I'd say by the time Martin Luther King was murdered in 68, that attitude had crystallized already among the black revolutionaries.

317
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:25,000
And I would say that when I first went to Barnard, 67, no, 66, in January, not January, September of 66, I don't think I would have called myself a revolutionary.

318
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:54,000
But then I would also not have, would not have been able to tell you that in January, in January of 66, when I was a sophomore at Barnard, that I had all the preparation to become a revolutionary. It was just a matter of a few more pieces of experience, a few more pieces of information, which once I met Eldridge Cleaver, who was a revolutionary, who was actually Marxist, although he kind of kept that to himself.

319
01:06:54,000 --> 01:07:20,000
He was a Marxist, and he had ideas of revolution and organization that was more radical in some senses than SNCC, given he was with a more, basically a revolutionary Marxist model. That was what was in his head.

320
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:49,000
And he saw the potential in the movement in the South, and he was originally a Southerner. So, but he and I fell in love and he wanted to, really say, he wanted me to come and visit him because once he was in Nashville during this riot, and he was a person, just been released from prison on parole, his parole officer made him come back immediately and said he couldn't go anywhere outside the city limits of San Francisco.

321
01:07:49,000 --> 01:08:04,000
That was his restriction. So, in order for us to have a relationship physically, I would have to actually enter into the city limits of San Francisco, which I did in later in July after our summer, the conference was in March.

322
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:18,000
We had all these student groups come, and it was an amazing collection of groups. One of the groups was the student union from Cornell, the ones who became famous with those photographs coming outside of straight hall with the guns.

323
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:32,000
That student group from, I think it was African American student organization. I'm not sure of their actual name, but the Black Student Group at Cornell was there. There was a Black Student Group from Berkeley, there was groups from Roosevelt University.

324
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:43,000
It was a very self-selected group of radical students that came there. This is not like the popular thing. This was the radical thing.

325
01:08:43,000 --> 01:09:03,000
It was actually, it was dangerous. I never really thought of the movement as dangerous. I guess if you commit to the movement, you accept that danger. That's part of the price, but the danger is just because you are challenging a tremendously powerful and injust society.

326
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:20,000
In terms of the broader range, SNCC was like a debating society or like an ideological institute as well as an activist group, as well as a family, as well as civil rights organizations.

327
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:42,000
So to think of SNCC as civil rights groups is not adequate. It's inadequate. It's also, it was phenomenon. It caused itself an organization, but it was right. It was committee. It was a difference in the committee and an organization. It was a committee and the personnel would fluctuate and you have different emphasis.

328
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:56,000
So by the time I came into SNCC, which is 67, it was a Black Power organization in transition to probably a revolutionary movement, but it was not going to be in that movement as an intact organization.

329
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:16,000
I didn't understand that, but I was in the midst of all of that. So I was absorbing so much. I was learning all about the thinking behind Black Power and the argument, the first argument that I got was Stokely's letter, not letter. The article he wrote, what we want.

330
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:35,000
During that time of the civil rights era leading up to the mid 60s, that was always this public question. What do you want? What do you people want? What is it you want? What is it you want? So when Stokely started saying, we want Black Power, you know what? It's tough asking. Nobody asked anymore.

331
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:56,000
He wrote an article. It was called What We Want. He articulated the view that he said that the issue integration does not deal with the issue of poverty. It only deals with the issue of color.

332
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:11,000
But the problem that the Black community faces is the absence of power and the absence of institutions. He said, you cannot have a legitimate social change when you say in order to have a good school, blacks have to go to a white school.

333
01:11:11,000 --> 01:11:20,000
In order to have a good, be in a good neighborhood, blacks have to go to a white neighborhood. He said integration is disintegration.

334
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:37,000
It was very clear. Now people can look back and say, oh yes, he was right. But at the time that wasn't obvious. Now integration is almost never mentioned. There's something that's no longer segregation.

335
01:11:37,000 --> 01:12:02,000
But this is not an integrated society. It's a society that has eliminated official segregation. At least in practice, in practical things, they haven't been able to eliminate the intellectual or emotional underpinnings of segregation in people's minds.

336
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:13,000
Either black or white. That's probably because it was instituted too long.

337
01:12:13,000 --> 01:12:32,000
So being in SNCC was a precursor to becoming a revolutionary and being able to come into the Black Panther Party, I didn't come into the Black Panther Party because I decided I wanted to be in the Black Panther Party.

338
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:54,000
I went out in July to visit Eldridge Cleaver. When I got there, he said, how long can you stay? I said, oh, maybe a week, 10 days, or whatever. He said, they're going to have to send Willie Ricks out here to get you back.

339
01:12:54,000 --> 01:13:13,000
So I ended up staying there basically through August. There was a little light, small riot in San Francisco that summer, maybe lasted like half a day.

340
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:23,000
That kind of rattled Eldridge. He just didn't want to be on parole. He felt constrained. He wanted to go to Cuba.

341
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:38,000
So I had met the Black Panthers that he was not supposed to be visiting because he was not only on parole, he couldn't associate with people who were armed and the Panthers were armed organizations, but also their office was in Oakland.

342
01:13:38,000 --> 01:13:48,000
He was instructed not to leave the confines of San Francisco. So as soon as I got there, he drove me over to Oakland and he could panthers.

343
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:57,000
The panthers had a lot of times that would come to his house. It was the summer of love. That was 1967.

344
01:13:57,000 --> 01:14:09,000
What I'm getting at is this notions of revolution hadn't really crystallized as much as they did later by after King's death and into 69.

345
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:21,000
By then, there wasn't really any snake and people had stopped talking about civil rights because the civil rights acted past.

346
01:14:21,000 --> 01:14:32,000
There was this interest in electoral politics that attracted a certain group of activists.

347
01:14:32,000 --> 01:14:56,000
But then this interest in organizing the community, the urban community, that was the movement that snake inspired but didn't, it couldn't implement because it was a committee.

348
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:11,000
So it put out ideas, it put out people. I think, for example, Bobby Rush, she was one of the Black Panthers leaders and Bob Brown, another one of the leaders in Chicago had been in snake.

349
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:23,000
I had been in snake. I think, Judeon Ford, one of the leaders of the Black Panther Party, early leader in New York, had been in snake and not Chicago in Boston.

350
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:33,000
The first chairman for the deputy chairman for the Panther office there, Panther Party there was Tiko Netlet, who was a freedom singer.

351
01:15:33,000 --> 01:15:49,000
So you see this gravitation through the vehicle of Black power into what we later call Black liberation or liberation movement in that era of 68, 67, 69, 70.

352
01:15:49,000 --> 01:15:55,000
And that was when I was most involved in the Black Panther Party and left the country in 69.

353
01:15:55,000 --> 01:16:14,000
And so the process of my involvement in direct involvement in what was going on in the United States was somewhat altered by Eldridge's decision once he was arrested in a shootout after the Oakland police.

354
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:21,000
There was a shootout with Oakland police in which one Panther was killed and I think about eight were arrested, including Eldridge.

355
01:16:21,000 --> 01:16:29,000
And he was the only ex-cundit in the group. So he was put back in prison. His parole was your vote.

356
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:38,000
He was able to get out in June of 1968 on a habeas petition, which was unbelievable. It was just totally unbelievable how that happened.

357
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:52,000
But it did happen. He got out. He was nominated the presidential candidate of the Peace and Freedom Party, although he wasn't old enough to have his name on the ballot.

358
01:16:52,000 --> 01:17:05,000
And Sol and Ice came out earlier that year. So his sort of his start was very big in the notion of challenge, Black power, revolution.

359
01:17:05,000 --> 01:17:16,000
And those things seemed to be extraordinarily threatening to the larger society, which enabled the FBI and the government to demonize us.

360
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:37,000
And it was okay to put us under attack. So that was the direction I was heading into. And in terms of our broader world outlook, it was very heavily influenced by what was happening in the Vietnam War.

361
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:58,000
That was the proof. That was the evidence of the United States as an imperial power. We could see it. We could see them sending troops to a foreign soil to shore up a government that was a puppet and to stop the communists who had won and prevent them from it.

362
01:17:58,000 --> 01:18:26,000
So we were in this world that's similar to what's here now. But it was a lot of deception, lies, confusion, hiding the ball, not telling the truth. But the media, the press, the newspapers, in terms of the Vietnam War, were more able than currently to give the story.

363
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:52,000
Because they had actual physical reporters physically going into the battlefield with the soldiers and filing reports. And we could see TV. We could see the war. We could see the massacres. We could see a horrible, horrible thing. My daughter was telling me, my daughter is now 41 years old. But at the time she was elementary school. And she said, that was traumatic.

364
01:18:52,000 --> 01:19:11,000
We would see this stuff on the news. It was horrifying. So it was maybe it was horrifying to her. But to us, it was evidence. Evidence that the United States was an imperialist, powered, the United States was reckless. The United States did disregard human rights.

365
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:26,000
It was proof that the things they were going to us, they do outside. But the other part of that, and this is the important thing for us, the revolutionaries, is that the Vietnamese showed they could be defeated.

366
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:52,000
And they weren't rich. And they weren't powerful. They were organized. In fact, I heard a comment that General Jep was reported to have made to an American during the negotiations for the end of the war. And he was told, but we won every battle. And he said, and it didn't matter.

367
01:19:52,000 --> 01:20:13,000
Because the Vietnamese understood the politics of liberation, and they understood the dynamics of the use of knowledge, of propaganda, of organization. They presented themselves in a way that essentially most countries supported Vietnam.

368
01:20:13,000 --> 01:20:39,000
Even if they weren't pro-communists, they supported the Vietnamese claim for independence over the American claim to dominate. So we were in that mode, which even Martin Luther King came out in a denounce the Vietnam War. So we were in a mode in which an anti-imperialist upheaval was triggered by Vietnam, sort of right as the Black Power Movement exploded.

369
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:55,000
We are back after a short break. You mentioned that you want to come at a further part of our conversation by the Paramanosian Period of Community Revolution.

370
01:20:55,000 --> 01:21:07,000
The way the movement has been taught has been problematic from my perspective, particularly in the way certain terms are used.

371
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:23,000
For example, talk about integration. The effort to put an end to the segregation of schools was not as far as Black communities were involved. A move to integration.

372
01:21:23,000 --> 01:21:43,000
It was a move to eliminate segregation to stop the oppressive exclusion. Now you could stop the oppressive exclusion several ways. Stop being oppressive, stop being inclusive, fund the Black schools wherever to the height, which is one of the choices.

373
01:21:43,000 --> 01:22:03,000
But integration, like merging these very separate societies, seemed to be a government idea, but it did not come from the Black community, it did not come from the Black movement.

374
01:22:03,000 --> 01:22:16,000
So ending racist terrorism, ending racist exclusion is not necessarily integration. So there was a problem there, the thinking of how we were going to go about our struggle.

375
01:22:16,000 --> 01:22:27,000
Now in the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee and in the areas that it worked, they were dealing with local people, local communities.

376
01:22:27,000 --> 01:22:45,000
And many cases the communities weren't terribly well educated or weren't that wealthy. And so you really ever heard this word integration in those communities, but what was going on in reality was all over the United States.

377
01:22:45,000 --> 01:23:09,000
And people, poor people who were Black and largely a lot of Black people were able to pull together after a long period of small steps that exploded up with the success of the bus boycott in Montgomery that stimulated all over the country people to take action.

378
01:23:09,000 --> 01:23:27,000
Not people whose names we know, but people who lived in this town, who had helped in some other program churches, there was a groundswell of activism going on across the United States, a process that I like to define as community revolution.

379
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:50,000
It was done by communities in communities and these communities could connect. And I say that because the way in which the Civil Rights Movement is has been, I don't know if still has been presented academically as a good movement until King died.

380
01:23:50,000 --> 01:24:19,000
And then a bad movement afterwards. And why is it bad because it's black? It's not for integration, it's calling itself black power and that's anti-white. And so, you know, this effort to protect what is white is really problematic because the real issue that we have been struggling with is it's profound hatred, resistance, and violence.

381
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:32,000
And the resistance, rejection, and destruction of Black people and Black communities. That's anti-black, that's anti-life, that's anti-social, that's horrible.

382
01:24:32,000 --> 01:24:41,000
So, the Black communities who under segregation and the whole country was segregated, not just the South.

383
01:24:41,000 --> 01:24:55,000
The Black communities under segregation developed mechanisms of survival and communication and how to manage. And there were leaders who evolved in all these communities many times and leaders were women.

384
01:24:56,000 --> 01:25:13,000
And when the Brown decision happened and there were so many organized efforts to change these horrendous practices, the people who were willing to take steps into the movement began to become predominant.

385
01:25:13,000 --> 01:25:25,000
Because before, I'll tell you, when early 60s, late 50s, a lot of Black people referred to the movement as that mess. You don't want to get involved with that mess.

386
01:25:25,000 --> 01:25:40,000
And so, as younger people in the communities who were willing to do it got older and then a few more people got bolder, you saw as the 60s progress more and more sort of standing up and challenges.

387
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:55,000
And you saw a plethora of organizations, you couldn't go to a community that had a significant Black community population without finding a lot of organizations, except maybe in a place like Oakland.

388
01:25:55,000 --> 01:26:06,000
You go to Oakland, there weren't many organizations. There were some, there was an NAACP, maybe. There was one, but it was just not a well organized community.

389
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:19,000
And they didn't have the structure of churches, they didn't have the structure of Black colleges. And so it had an openness. It had an openness that I loved it. When I saw this, it's like no one's organized here.

390
01:26:19,000 --> 01:26:29,000
And so there was this enthusiastic group of people who were young, who've been watching television and they'd heard about the movement and they were willing to do something.

391
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:43,000
And those were the young people who flocked into the Black Panther Party in Oakland. Some of them told me, well that was the thing to do, to go to the demonstrations. It became popular to be a Black Panther. And people wanted to be Panthers.

392
01:26:43,000 --> 01:26:54,000
And young people wanted to be Panthers. They wanted to come to the Rality. They wanted to learn this. And you know, some of them actually joined the movement and some of them were just influenced by it.

393
01:26:54,000 --> 01:27:09,000
What I wanted to say is there was a process by which communities that were working class predominantly, not highly educated, but educated to some extent, and aware, and knew that the country was talking about them.

394
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:22,000
And then those are the communities whose children were being shuttled off to fight and be it not. I mean, all the, not all, but the vast majority of soldiers were teenagers taken out of high schools, out of poor neighborhoods.

395
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:50,000
Very, very few college kids went because they could get exemptions. And so that destabilized a lot of communities. And then the return to the communities of heroin-addicted soldiers and people who had horrendous traumatic stress issues.

396
01:27:50,000 --> 01:28:02,000
And who were victorious heroes was devastating in a lot of ways. When I say devastating, I meant the way it harmed the community.

397
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:23,000
And so to talk about civil rights as if it's separate to black power is a mistake in my mind that the issue was how do poor people, black people, excluded people, organized themselves so they can empower and gain recognition, gain political voice.

398
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:38,000
And kind of what we were doing, snake people were doing it in one way, SCLC was doing it in a different way, the NAACP, NAACP is actually doing something else because it's elitist in the sense of a leetist legal action, NAACP legal defense fund.

399
01:28:38,000 --> 01:28:47,000
Whereas the NAACP was more of a membership organization, but they had very distinct limits as to what they would and wouldn't do.

400
01:28:47,000 --> 01:29:01,000
We have a spectrum of organizations and you'll see, for example, one of the most powerful, dramatic, inspiring leaders, the Black Panther Party ever produced was Fred Hampton.

401
01:29:01,000 --> 01:29:11,000
Fred Hampton was in the youth council of the NAACP. He was a leader there. I found out that Fred Hampton was a leader when he was in elementary school.

402
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:20,000
Fred Hampton found out that there were kids in his elementary school who didn't get any breakfast. He invited him to his house. He fixed breakfast for him.

403
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:29,000
And I said, that's amazing. This is a man that later joins an organization that actually has something called free breakfast for children.

404
01:29:29,000 --> 01:29:40,000
But he was thinking that way before he ever heard of the Black Panther. So we have this absurd of energy, of ideas, of possibility.

405
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:54,000
The world in which colonialism is being repudiated in Africa, is being repudiated in Asia, there's movements, uprisings in Mexico, in Brazil.

406
01:29:54,000 --> 01:30:06,000
Now they're not all successful. In fact, most of these uprisings aren't successful, but China. That revolution was a success. Cuba, that was a success.

407
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:17,000
So the sense that it was possible for ordinary people to make a fundamental difference in their life. We had proof that that could happen. We had opportunity to make it happen.

408
01:30:17,000 --> 01:30:29,000
And we had an energized group of young people and some middle-aged people and even some old people. In the Black Panther Party, we had one member who was like in the 50s.

409
01:30:30,000 --> 01:30:42,000
But what I'm saying is that there was this energy circulating through the community. Sometimes, as call civil rights, Black Power was more confrontational.

410
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:55,000
And just because a person didn't go to the Black Power rallies or didn't wear African headdresses or didn't say, so brother, that didn't mean that that didn't affect them.

411
01:30:55,000 --> 01:31:11,000
So we were having a cultural process, an educational process that was influencing our community. And I think by consequence, it was influencing the way the larger white community perceived the Black community.

412
01:31:11,000 --> 01:31:20,000
Now, the more friendly types, they perceive this as probably a good thing. But that's the minority.

413
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:30,000
The vast majority of whites just know about Black people from what they read in the papers. And the papers were slanted. The FBI was writing all kinds of horrible things about the Panthers.

414
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:43,000
Or they had not the FBI was writing. The FBI had reporters and the major papers who would write slant stories and they would plant stories and they use, this is a term that's called Black Propaganda.

415
01:31:43,000 --> 01:32:07,000
And use the media to demonize people improperly. And so the fact that the Black Panther Party, which was started, I'm talking about the Black Panther Party for self-defense, which was started in Oakland in October of 1967.

416
01:32:07,000 --> 01:32:22,000
No, I'm sorry, October of 1966. It was started on October 21st because that was Bobby Seals birthday. He said he remembered coming home after writing up. He and he had written up their 10 point platform and program and he went home.

417
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:35,000
And this brother said, surprise, the birthday. So he remembered. But so and the Black Panther Party for self-defense took that name, Black Panther, from the Lounge County Group.

418
01:32:35,000 --> 01:32:53,000
The Lounge County Group called itself the Lounge County Freedom Organization, LCFO. But the logo was this Panther and the media called it the Black Panther Party. And so then they started calling it the Black Panther Party and to the Tour of the Leaver for the Black Panther.

419
01:32:53,000 --> 01:33:12,000
So what I want you to see is here people in Alabama have a Black Panther Party. And people in Oakland have a Black Panther Party and they are in communication even though they're not trying to do the same way. And there was other Black Panther parties. And this name, Black Panther became part of the symbol for Black Power.

420
01:33:12,000 --> 01:33:35,000
But then there are other groups, for example, in Kansas City. A group was consolidated, the joined with the Black Panther Party. And Pete O'Neill was the chairman of this group. And then there was some dispute, which I don't know the details of, some dispute between Pete O'Neill and Oakland Panthers.

421
01:33:35,000 --> 01:34:04,000
So he pulled his group out and said, we're going to call ourselves the sons of Malcolm. And so you see these formations all over the country in urban areas that involve Black men and Black women. You also see the Nation of Islam, which is much more conservative. You see Black elected officials, Daining. So there's a ferment. There's a ferment going on. And then also there's young white activists with the SDS, a huge student organization.

422
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:15,000
And the anti-war movement. Now the anti-war movement kind of consolidates all this because they're just, well, it's actually the anti-draft movement, but they call it the anti-war movement, mobilization against the war.

423
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:33,000
That was being inspired in part by what was happening in the Black community. And of course, there's tensions and at the time it didn't seem that it was so effective. But the FBI and the intelligence agencies were, they were going crazy.

424
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:46,000
Part of the reason they were going crazy, in my opinion, is because the United States during that period was also at war. So that's a different intelligence, the national security issue. What was happening there at war with communists.

425
01:34:46,000 --> 01:35:04,000
And all of these groups, like Sokli Karmichel, it was a chairman of SNCC, he goes to visit the communist Castro. And the Black Panthers go to Canada and have meetings with these communists, Vietnamese. And this, you know, so like the United States has genuine enemies.

426
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:24,000
And they are sort of using their attitude toward their enemies to paint the Panthers who are too radical for them. And also they want to get, I'll give you an example, I want lackeys is what I was going to use. But what they want is their advocate.

427
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:50,000
So a good case of what I'm talking about is when Malcolm X goes to visit Africa, he makes a visit to the organization of African unity and he speaks there and he visits several heads of state in Africa. And that's written about, and we read about it and we're very proud of Malcolm X and he comes back and he talks about, if Africa he talked about the interests, he talked about colonialism.

428
01:35:50,000 --> 01:36:11,000
So what does the United States government do? They find James Farmer, who was ahead of core. And they send him to Africa because they don't like the fact of what Malcolm was doing in Africa. They don't like the alignments that Malcolm is making. So they want to have their own version. And so we see that, like they'll have, they want to counter.

429
01:36:11,000 --> 01:36:36,000
So if Snick becomes exceptionally radical, they'll find ways, well how can we fund this or arrange this so we have a counter. So these are the kind of things that we're going on. And that's understandable politically. Then there's another secret level of what was going on with the intelligence agencies, with the FBI and the DI, defense intelligence agency and the national security agency.

430
01:36:36,000 --> 01:36:59,000
One of the things that they were worried about was any potential alliances between black, what they call black militants, African revolutionary, African and Arab revolutionaries. This is something they were very worried about because it's sort of like, then it's like not containable.

431
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:28,000
So they wanted to make sure that didn't happen. So I happened to be married to Elders, Gleiber, who went to Cuba and then to Algeria and we set up an international section of the black Panther Party in Algeria, the support of the government there. And what we were doing, we were meeting the African and the Arab revolutionaries. And you know, organized. So we were going completely counter. Now for the FBI and the CIA and these intelligence agencies, we have become a part of the government.

432
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:53,000
Well, enemies, but it's worse than that. It's, it's, it's, how did they call it? Key extremists. They had lists of key extremists. They had a whole counter intelligence operation targeted to every form of activism that they disagreed with.

433
01:37:53,000 --> 01:38:17,000
So there was a co-entail pro for feminism. There was a co-entail pro for new left students, a co-entail pro for the socialists. Co-entail pro started out back in the 50s with the Communist Party. She got to the point, she was a joke in my household. Every third person in the Communist Party was working for the FBI. They're the ones who filled the meetings.

434
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:38,000
And so the black Panther Party, the black Panther Party came into existence in 1966, co-entail pro domestic, the FBI's co-entail pro against not, you know, something more than the Communist Party, came into existence in 1967, I believe.

435
01:38:38,000 --> 01:38:56,000
And they, one of their key objectives was to prevent what they said, the rise of a black Messiah that could unify the black masses. So this means that they're looking at what's going on in our community revolution and our civil rights and our black power. They're looking at it as a political problem.

436
01:38:56,000 --> 01:39:14,000
And they're singling out the people who they think would be the most problem. Now, who they listed at the beginning was, well, they said there's a lie to Muhammad, but he's a little old. Now Malcolm X is already dead.

437
01:39:14,000 --> 01:39:24,000
So Elijah Muhammad, he's a little old. It was Max Stanford who was the head of Revolutionary Action Movement, which was an underground group based in Philadelphia.

438
01:39:24,000 --> 01:39:39,000
It was Stokely Carmichael, Heather Snick, and there was Martin Luther King, who they were really, really, really worried about because well, King didn't alienate anyone.

439
01:39:39,000 --> 01:39:49,000
And he drew millions and millions of people and had a Nobel Prize. He had much more worldwide admiration than any of these other people on their list.

440
01:39:49,000 --> 01:40:01,000
And then there's the, they didn't even have the black Panthers in there. And in part because the black Panthe Party was collective in the sense that we didn't ever have just one leader.

441
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:30,000
We'd have a whole committee of leaders. And then every group that was organized, every chapter would have, you know, like a deputy minister of defense, deputy minister of information, communication secretary, education secretary, minister of culture, and, you know, and then captains. And so it was, it was a structured group that this structure, this leadership structure would be duplicated. And what the government found out in the first efforts because usually they see black organizations that are confident.

442
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:54,000
And the way they're going to do it is scare you or kill you. So they tried, they tried killing Huey Newton. He just got wounded and ended up in a shootout and a policeman ended up dead. So it's okay. We'll convict him of murder. I don't do it. He'll go to the gas chamber. I'll be the end of Huey Newton.

443
01:40:54,000 --> 01:41:13,000
So when he was arrested and charged with murder, this was in 1967. It was in October, I believe, toward the end of October. It was a few weeks after Che Guevara was found killed and murdered in Bolivia.

444
01:41:13,000 --> 01:41:29,000
And what we did, and when I say we, it's a small handful of people, maybe eight of us decided that my suggestion, we had to have demonstrations at the courthouse.

445
01:41:29,000 --> 01:41:42,000
This is not something the small group of black pastors, they weren't into demonstrations. That wasn't the thing. But I said, well, I understood that demonstrations are a way to protect you against violence.

446
01:41:42,000 --> 01:42:03,000
And also to help build support, to bring support into the organization. So now they're faced with a need to protect Huey Newton from what might happen. And we organized and participated. We started out with about eight people and ended up with international movement.

447
01:42:03,000 --> 01:42:29,000
And by the time his case went to trial, and that is the kind of activity that frightened the government. That was the part I think I didn't understand. The government was frightened. The police were frightened. The FBI was frightened. They had never encountered agitated, armed, angry, intelligent, articulate black people standing up and telling them what they would and wouldn't do.

448
01:42:29,000 --> 01:42:58,000
That's not an experience they knew what to do with. They had that experience colonial regimes had that experience. And as I've studied other movements, I see there, you know, like there's the early phase of the people who are the most like the colonialists and they want the legal rights. And then ultimately it goes to mass movement. And then it goes to guerrilla warfare and then it goes to independence. And then it goes to neo-colonialism, unfortunately.

449
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:14,000
But what I'm saying is it was a world process that the FBI and the intelligence agencies and their counterintelligence programs put us in that warfare context that they had been dealing with that we didn't know about.

450
01:43:14,000 --> 01:43:23,000
I should have known a little bit, but I didn't because my father was in the government. But I was a kid. I wasn't paying an attention to what he was doing until much later.

451
01:43:23,000 --> 01:43:37,000
And I said, oh my god, you're doing all these things. It's very political. I mean, he was helping the United States government put an end to communist absurd uprisings in the Philippines and the Blue Community Development.

452
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:56,000
And so I guess we were we were sparks in a movement that was much bigger than what we actually understood. And it was us. It was the most extraordinary, exciting and wonderful thing we could do.

453
01:43:56,000 --> 01:44:19,000
And we also knew we were risking our lives, but we did it on we wanted to do it. We wanted to make sure that these conditions had to come to an end. And we were going to put an end to them or we were going to die trying. And that's an attitude that is frightening to people in authority.

454
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:44,000
I want to ask a couple things. And you've spoken in some measure already, but maybe you can focus in and just illustrate in one or two. I'm so struck when I think about your arrival in late 67 in Oakland. And you've mentioned obviously that the unions arrested already and on a capital charge.

455
01:44:44,000 --> 01:45:01,000
All of what will happen there in what really are not too many months. There's a swirl of things happening. The ideology of the party is going to move through these nuance with very significant transitions if you stop and think about their implication.

456
01:45:01,000 --> 01:45:14,000
It's quickly internationalized and it's focused. The pressure from law enforcement through Coentele Probe of the Oakland, but it's just it's just ever present and massive.

457
01:45:14,000 --> 01:45:26,000
And you're a very young person who becomes in many ways part of the apparatus to explain all of this to report all of this to speak all of it.

458
01:45:26,000 --> 01:45:46,000
Well, you said I was very young to the panthers. I was older. One friend of mine said, cheers and hi. Most of the panthers were high schools age. And she came from Chicago to Oakland. I think she was 17. And she's so cat thing she was 22. She could be a leader.

459
01:45:46,000 --> 01:46:07,000
I'm interested in how if you can illustrate the that climate and you've spoken this over that. I think in particular difficulties of trying to carry forward a broad progressive political program to the that locusts of the.

460
01:46:07,000 --> 01:46:19,000
At a time when when the police pressure the criminal pressure basically is just smashing down upon you.

461
01:46:19,000 --> 01:46:26,000
Now you want me to articulate that process how we were doing it what what it was like.

462
01:46:26,000 --> 01:46:31,000
You said earlier, you just press forward.

463
01:46:31,000 --> 01:46:51,000
Let me let me let me think about this because what the black panther party for self defense started with a small group of maybe four well actually started with two two guys and then another one joined and then the girl joined but it's so it started very small.

464
01:46:51,000 --> 01:47:05,000
It was local was only an Oakland. But the concepts it began with were for the entire black community. We want power to determine the destiny of our own community.

465
01:47:05,000 --> 01:47:25,000
And when you look at the 10 point platform and program it's essentially reform. And it's analogous to all the other sets of demands. If you look at the points that they raised in Atlanta student movement. We want to into police brutality. We want them to employ us.

466
01:47:25,000 --> 01:47:41,000
We want to stop not letting us try on clothes and department stores. I mean the different you look at colonial statements of the independence desires when you go back to the colored people's conventions at the end of the Civil War.

467
01:47:41,000 --> 01:48:03,000
You'll see what do you want we want to be treated the same as white. We want to be able to own land. We want essentially the black panther party was a 20th century version of the hopes and demand and desires of an oppressed black community re articulated in a new set of words.

468
01:48:03,000 --> 01:48:24,000
And the young people who joined the black panther party were young people like me who had seen civil rights activists being attacked, being beaten, being killed. People the same ages themselves are younger.

469
01:48:24,000 --> 01:48:50,000
And so that had a huge, huge effect. Many people that I met who are older than me told me that what made them join the Civil Rights Movement was the murder of Emmett Till. But that happened in 1955. So there's the people who were Emmett Till's age who were 15 or 14 and 55. Those are the ones who went into the Civil Rights Movement because there wasn't any black power movement yet.

470
01:48:50,000 --> 01:49:08,000
So the kids who came into the black panther party a little older and they one of the dynamics that's intriguing to me is that so many of the urban areas if you talk about let's say Philadelphia or New York or Chicago or Los Angeles.

471
01:49:08,000 --> 01:49:28,000
The black population, the working class black population in these big cities has a large number of migrants from the South. So you have children whose parents left the South or grandparents left the South who may have family still in the South.

472
01:49:28,000 --> 01:49:56,000
So when you see these demonstrations like people watching what's happening in Birmingham that affects them in a way that it doesn't affect let's say somebody just watching on television. It's not just news. It's first of all is traumatizing to see these people being beaten. And I remember Emory Douglas who grew up in Michigan when he was young before his mother moved to California. He said, I didn't want that to happen to me.

473
01:49:56,000 --> 01:50:24,000
I wouldn't let anybody beat me like that. And so you have this edge. You say, well, this is what they did to girls and boys who just went out and protested. They beat them, they chased them, they said, sick dogs on. So you have anger to resolve or rectify this kind of violence. And also this sense of, I wouldn't let anybody do that to me.

474
01:50:24,000 --> 01:50:38,000
If they come and push me around, I'm fighting back. And so when the Black Panther Party took the position as in the name, Black Panther Party for self-defense, this automatic response, that's right, we can defend ourselves. We should be able to defend ourselves.

475
01:50:38,000 --> 01:50:49,000
Now, if someone was going up in Mississippi, first of all, they're not even going to hear about the Black Panther Party. And secondly, this whole idea of being able to defend yourself, everybody knows it but doesn't anybody talk about it.

476
01:50:49,000 --> 01:51:07,000
So you had a generation who sort of threw off the caution of their parents and were thrust into the middle of a country at war, the Vietnam War. And if they were younger, this is why the age, they were too young in many cases to get drafted.

477
01:51:07,000 --> 01:51:19,000
They were 14 and 15 and 16. In fact, some of them were 13. We didn't really like to have 13 year olds and then there were those who lied and say they were older. But the Black Panthers were largely a youth movement.

478
01:51:19,000 --> 01:51:36,000
And youth have several qualities that are distinct. One of them is they believe in a mortal. And so even though it's very, very dangerous, what we were doing, it was like,

479
01:51:37,000 --> 01:51:48,000
okay, I'm going to get my gun and we're going to do it out. It's like they didn't really think. And I'm trying to think myself.

480
01:51:48,000 --> 01:52:01,000
It's sort of like I know people are going to get killed. I know that. I know I might get killed, but that didn't function as a deterrent on us. Now, that does function as a deterrent for most people.

481
01:52:01,000 --> 01:52:14,000
So what you have with the Black Panthers and a similar group is a radical, committed, dedicated group of young people who are collective. They've collected together. And that's a huge energy.

482
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:28,000
That's that collective communal energy. And they represent adults who aren't going to join the party, but who are going to help them and support them. And they also, because the Panthers ran out there the way they did.

483
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:49,000
I'm quoting from a woman who is a Sadist Shakur wrote about in her book, her, her, her autobiography. This is when she was being, her picture was being circulated all over New York as a person who was wanted for bank robbery.

484
01:52:49,000 --> 01:53:01,000
But she didn't know that they were going to put her picture in the paper that day. She wasn't actually the person around the bank. But that's who they were looking for.

485
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:16,000
So she goes by her apartment and she sees police all over it. So she said, I can't go there. And she goes to a friend. She said, nobody knows that I have this friend.

486
01:53:16,000 --> 01:53:27,000
Her phone number is not in my address book. So I'm going to go to her house. So she goes to her house and the girl says, so what took you so long?

487
01:53:27,000 --> 01:53:38,000
So that's what I meant that there's people who are observing this stuff, who will help. They're just not going to let it be publicly known.

488
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:54,000
And then there are people who can't help but be involved. And those are the people they have to be eye just messed over like your parents or your neighbors or your friends call them up. Have you seen them? Where are they? What can you tell us?

489
01:53:54,000 --> 01:54:02,000
And that's to alienate those people from you. I'm trying to think of something. What's that a cousin of mine?

490
01:54:02,000 --> 01:54:17,000
I just heard recently they found out that so and so was related to me. We're cousins. I think our my father's side of the family is related through that.

491
01:54:17,000 --> 01:54:32,000
And he had some kind of security clearance in the Navy. And he was called in because they found out that he, you know, these types of things. I don't even know what we're going on.

492
01:54:32,000 --> 01:54:47,000
I discovered my son. The sail cleaver. His name is in the Mississippi sovereignty commission records. They're spying on my son. I don't think my son's even been in Mississippi.

493
01:54:47,000 --> 01:55:05,000
But what I'm saying is that the level of surveillance and what it called the sea, we will get back now to the nature of a slave society. The society in which how did they, how did they put it?

494
01:55:05,000 --> 01:55:21,000
South African, South African sociologist said it practices and who's describing South Africa, but he can use this United States. It's a society in which there is democracy for the white and tyranny for the blacks.

495
01:55:21,000 --> 01:55:36,000
And so the political system that black people are subjected to does not have the liberty or the freedom of motion or the freedom of access that the whites do.

496
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:46,000
And then when they start acting like they do, or the they ought to, it becomes very frightened. So we were setting off fears that we didn't quite understand.

497
01:55:46,000 --> 01:55:59,000
But we when when I'm done with this. We're back for a final kind of question. Mr. Rowland, I want to just invite you to come in on the following. We're at we're at 40 plus years distance now from the late 60s.

498
01:55:59,000 --> 01:56:17,000
And we're able to talk about all of this with that much space in time that has passed. And I think that probably in significant in significant ways changes even the moment of explaining it.

499
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:34,000
There's I think in this context of things I've read that you wrote in those years at the time. At the time. And the the immediacy and the lawness of it and the urgency of it.

500
01:56:34,000 --> 01:56:52,000
And the uglyness of the things you had to talk about and describe to make you know what you were confronting. And at this distance, even when we talk about horrible things that happen to people that we knew that you knew, there's just enough removed somehow that I think the emotional character of the telling is a little different.

501
01:56:52,000 --> 01:57:07,000
I wonder so I want to ask you to reflect on that if the distance has changed the way we talk about this. And what and if it has what that means for how we try to cover that history. That's one broad thing.

502
01:57:07,000 --> 01:57:22,000
The thing too is is before we started day, we touched on the fact that there is a film now kind of coming into circulation, the black robics tape. And it's engaged by different people in different and interesting ways.

503
01:57:22,000 --> 01:57:45,000
And so is it nostalgia, is it historic interest, is it why do these things resonate the way that they do different audiences. So two broad things. What the passage of time is meant to the way we think and talk about these things. And how we in the specific case of this documentary, how it plays to today's audience.

504
01:57:45,000 --> 01:58:00,000
At the time when these police raids were an everyday occurrence and Panther offices were getting bombed and people were being followed and shot and arrested.

505
01:58:00,000 --> 01:58:25,000
There's a newspaper cover of one of the issues of the black Panther newspaper. I think it's a 1970 issue. It's something about fascism in America. And you open it up and there's this page after page after page after page of arrests. Records of arrests, who was arrested, what they were charged with, where they were like, like, Moumia Abu Jammal, one case in point, comes from Philadelphia to Oakland.

506
01:58:25,000 --> 01:58:45,000
And he's arrested for jail walking because he's a black Panther. He's a teenager. He's got a picture of the Philadelphia police have a picture of him. And I think they give it to the FBI, a teenager, a teenager who made a speech at a rally wearing a black beret against the Vietnam War.

507
01:58:45,000 --> 01:59:05,000
And the FBI's picture, they wrote a number and on the back did. So the hatred and hostility of the law enforcement community and the FBI, I think, was more exaggerated than maybe the general population.

508
01:59:05,000 --> 01:59:28,000
But that was the element that we kept referring to as the, well, a hearing Newton calling the racist dog police or the fascist police or the imperialism. We were engaged with them at the time. They were engaged with us. It was a war. It was what's to call low intensity counterinsurgency warfare techniques.

509
01:59:28,000 --> 01:59:52,000
It was being targeted toward us. But we were revolutionaries and we believed that it would come to war and that we will take that risk. And so I think that has something to do with the tone of how we expressed ourselves the things that we wrote about in our newspapers.

510
01:59:52,000 --> 02:00:09,000
And it was attitude because so many people were going to jail, going to prison, getting arrested. It was overwhelming to certain extent. It wasn't overwhelming when we thought of what we wanted to see happen. Our vision for America.

511
02:00:09,000 --> 02:00:38,000
And in the distance when you come back now, I think the fact that so many of the people who made that time, who led that time, whose voices, whether they were speakers or whether they were leaders or whether they were artists or whether they were singers like Mary and the Kaba, or maybe Ossie Davis or Stokely Carmichael.

512
02:00:39,000 --> 02:01:04,000
All these people are gone. They're all passed away. And so the intensity that we had at that time has diminished somewhat because we don't have that collection of powerful, brilliant, artistic, committed people.

513
02:01:04,000 --> 02:01:19,000
We don't have that collection anymore. I mean, if just imagine all those people who were together at the same time, suppose, okay, let's talk about people who were killed and supposed to weren't. Let's say, suppose Bobby Kennedy wasn't killed.

514
02:01:19,000 --> 02:01:34,000
Suppose Malcolm X wasn't killed. Suppose Martin Luther King wasn't killed. Suppose Fred Hampton wasn't killed. And suppose the organizations that all those people represented flourished.

515
02:01:34,000 --> 02:01:42,000
Then we'd be talking something. We have a different outcome. And we'd be talking in a different way. And we'd be a different country.

516
02:01:42,000 --> 02:02:06,000
So they were killed. So we aren't going to be that different country. And I think that's probably has something to do with why that the images in Black Power Mix tape are appealing to people because I think, you know, the opportunity to be that country is gone.

517
02:02:07,000 --> 02:02:27,000
However, when you watch Black Power Mix tape, it looks like it's still a possible. And everyone's young. And Angela is so smart and stokely, so charming. And it's engaging. People were engaging. Even though it's a very threatening and dangerous time, the personalities were engaging. And they were upbeat.

518
02:02:27,000 --> 02:02:47,000
Like almost all the pictures you see are stokely Carmack, or just smile. He's got a beautiful, beautiful smile. And people also were young. But they're just young and full of hormones and excitement. And yeah, we want to have revolution, but we want to have go to party too.

519
02:02:47,000 --> 02:02:57,000
And we want to get married and we want to have kids and elders just say, they're just wasting our time. Let's get this stuff over with so we can go back to enjoying our life.

520
02:03:06,000 --> 02:03:14,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

